1 Subset Selection

The leaps::regsubsets function performs an exhaustive search for the best subsets of the variables in x for predicting y in a Linear Regression setting, using an efficient branch-and-bound algorithm. It chooses the best subset based on RSS. See ?leaps::regsubsets.

regfit.full <- leaps::regsubsets(Salary ~ ., Hitters)

# Best two-variable model contains 
# Hits and CRBI features
summary(regfit.full)

The leaps package has a has a built in S3 plot method for class regsubsets which can be used to display the selected variables for the best model for a given number of predictors, ranked according to \(R^2\). See ?plot.regsubsets.

par(mfrow = c(2, 2))
plot(regfit.full, scale = "r2")
plot(regfit.full, scale = "adjr2")
plot(regfit.full, scale = "Cp")
plot(regfit.full, scale = "bic")

coef(regfit.full, 6)

regfit.best <- leaps::regsubsets(Salary ~ . ,
                                 data = Hitters[train, ],
                                 nvmax = 19)
test.mat <- model.matrix(Salary ~ ., data = Hitters[test,])

1.2.1 Define a S3 predict method

There is no predict method for objects of class regbubsets, so we will create our own to replicated the steps above and simplify things moving forward. S3 methods are not complicated, they just define a specific behavior for a given class object (first argument) they act on.

predict.regsubsets <- function(object, newdata, id, ...) {
  form <- as.formula(object$call[[2]])
  #print(form)
  mat   <- model.matrix(form, newdata)
  coefi <-coef(object, id = id)
  xvars <-names(coefi)
  mat[, xvars]%*%coefi
}

cv.errors <- matrix(NA, k, 19, dimnames = list(NULL, paste(1:19)))

# k-fold cross validation
for (j in 1:k) {
  best.fit <- leaps::regsubsets(Salary ~ .,
                                data = Hitters[folds!=j, ],
                                nvmax = 19)
  # Loop over best models with 1 to 19 predictors
  for (i in 1:19) {
    pred <- predict(best.fit, Hitters[folds==j, ], id = i)
    cv.errors[j, i] <- mean((Hitters$Salary[folds==j] - pred)^2)
  }

# Create training and test sets

n      <- nrow(x)
train  <- sample(1:n, n/2)
test   <-(-train)

# Estimating the test error
ridge.mod <- glmnet(x[train,], y[train],
                    alpha = 0, lambda = grid,
                    thresh = 1e-12)
ridge.pred <- predict(ridge.mod, s = 4, newx = x[test,])
